00:12:38.039 --> 00:12:44.919
West region. The benefit here is, I didn't as the application developer, I didn't have to do this

00:12:44.919 --> 00:12:50.520
logic myself. I don't have to go through and write a bunch of code that says, if user is in group B,

00:12:50.520 --> 00:12:55.719
show only this data. If user is in group C, only show this data. I've seen that pattern.

00:12:55.719 --> 00:13:00.840
It works, but it's brittle. And it's full of security issues and challenges.

00:13:00.840 --> 00:13:05.400
Here, we're relying on Snowflake to manage all the data governance and access control.

00:13:05.400 --> 00:13:10.520
PositConnect just forwards on the identity of the logged in user. And Snowflake uses that

00:13:10.520 --> 00:13:14.840
as it returns results of the queries that are being executed. So the only data coming back

