the time over to Jonathan to cover this a little bit more in depth. But the concept of Orbital is

00:14:02.679 --> 00:14:09.640
to say, I've taken some data, I've created a local extract of it, and I've trained some sort of

00:14:09.640 --> 00:14:14.039
machine learning or statistical model on that data. Maybe it's a tree-based model, maybe it's

00:14:14.039 --> 00:14:19.880
some sort of regression analysis, whatever it is, I have this final model object, and that model

00:14:19.880 --> 00:14:25.559
object will allow me to generate predictions on new data. Now, if you've used the tidy models

00:14:25.559 --> 00:14:31.640
framework or have read about it or are familiar with it to some extent, one of the advantages

00:14:31.640 --> 00:14:37.159
that that framework offers is it gives you the ability to not only train and tune a model itself,

00:14:37.159 --> 00:14:42.840
but to also embed within that model definition any pre-processing that takes place prior to the

00:14:42.840 --> 00:14:50.119
model fit. So if I normalized values, if I imputed missing values, if I did anything clever in my

00:14:50.119 --> 00:14:55.479
pre-processing to prepare the data to generate the best possible model, all of that can be captured

00:14:55.960 --> 00:15:03.799
in this tidy models object that I end up with. What Orbital does, and I'll mention this caveat

00:15:03.799 --> 00:15:07.719
up front, it only works for certain model types, and these are well documented on the website

00:15:07.719 --> 00:15:13.479
documentation, but what Orbital does is it will take this trained R model object that we have

00:15:14.200 --> 00:15:21.000
and convert that object into native SQL, which means that in the context of Snowflake, I can

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:26.760
take this model definition that typically would require me to have access to an R runtime in order

00:15:26.760 --> 00:15:33.000
to run and generate new predictions, and instead I can turn that definition into a SQL statement

00:15:33.559 --> 00:15:39.960
that I can then store within Snowflake as a view perhaps or a stored procedure, and now all of a

00:15:39.960 --> 00:15:45.960
sudden my model execution and prediction is not happening in R session somewhere, it's happening

00:15:45.960 --> 00:15:50.840
in a Snowflake warehouse, and it's happening lightning fast because it's part of Snowflake's

00:15:50.840 --> 00:15:55.719
native dialect. It's happening in SQL, it's well defined in SQL, Snowflake's query optimization

00:15:55.719 --> 00:16:02.039
works, everything that Snowflake does well comes into play, and we've seen dramatic results

00:16:02.039 --> 00:16:07.479
with a number of different customer accounts where model prediction pipelines that previously took

00:16:07.479 --> 00:16:13.320
days, hours or days, now take seconds or minutes, and it's been a dramatic time savings because

00:16:13.880 --> 00:16:18.119
we're able to take advantage of the full compute capability of what Snowflake warehouses have to

